Operator's hypothesis of a loose encoder cable is not supported: /odom/pose x shows a smooth, continuous ramp with no dropout, stale readings, or discontinuities throughout the 20-second bag. If an encoder cable were loose, we would expect missing data, zero-velocity segments, or erratic odometry — none of which are present.

The true root cause is PID integral saturation. At t≈12 s, a large reference step creates a massive position error. The integral term accumulates without bound, driving cmd_vel to its limit (0.8) and all PWM channels to 255. The output remains saturated well past the point where the error has decreased, indicating the integral is still unwinding.

Recommended fix (pseudocode):

  // In the PID update function:
  if (abs(output) < output_limit) {
      integral += error * dt;
  }
  integral = clamp(integral, -integral_max, integral_max);

Also consider adding a feedforward term for the reference trajectory so the feedback controller does not bear the full burden of large setpoint changes.
